The `setState` method in React is used to update the state of a component. The state of a component is a collection of data that is used to determine the rendering of the component. The state can be updated by adding, removing or changing the values of the data.

The `setState` function takes two arguments: a function that takes the previous state as an argument and returns the new state, and an optional callback function that is executed after the state is updated.

The `state` property of a component is read-only, so you cannot directly change its values. Instead, you must use the `setState` method to update the state.

Here is an example of updating an array's properties using `setState`:

```javascript
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = {
      items: [
        { id: 1, name: 'Apple' },
        { id:2, name: 'Banana' },
        {id:3, name: 'Orange' }
      ]
    };
  }

  handleAddItem = () => {
    this.setState(prevState => ({
      items: [...prevState.items, { id: 4, name: 'Grapes' }]
    }));
  }


  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <button onClick={this.handleAddItem}>Add Item</button>
        <ul>
          {this.state.items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```

In this example, we have a `MyComponent` that has a state property called `items`. When the `handleAddItem` function is called, the `setState` function is called with a function that returns a new state object. The new state object adds a new item to the `items` array with a `name` property of `Grapes`. The `render` function then renders the `items` array using the `map` function to create a list of `<li>` elements.

